        [
          "A web critic who devoted life, then afterlife to taking apart the movies and works of more talented artists.",
          "",
          "",
          "",
          "",
          "",
          "",
          "",
          "Logan Boese"
        ],
        [
          "Staff Generated History"
        ],
        [
          "They've always loved Movies. From being a latchkey kid, always awake as early as possible on Sunday mornings, to being a fledgling young film maker, with little more than a camera and a dream. Film school helped, but you never quite got your work to the level that they wanted it to be at. A series of small projects and workaday jobs followed, moving back in with the parents, your enthusiasm never dimming even while their bank account shrank and your prospects seemed irrevocably to lessen. Your stroke of luck came when the smallest of their projects gained a following. One that quickly outstripped not only all their previous work, but absolutely everything you'd ever done to that point. It was little more than an internet review show picking apart their favourite movies as a child, (in a notable, and over-the-top exagerration of your persona), but people seemed to like it. Ten years later, it had grown beyond anything they'd ever dreamed of. Not only did it provide them a decent living, but a website and community had built itself up around their show. This was great, until a particular fan made their way to their door. A film director whose work they had critiqued had watched the video and, surprisingly, not only agreed with their points, but felt that their grasp on story structure, narrative pacing, and character was so great, that they needed to be preserved for all eternity. You were embraced, not necessarily for their performance or what they'd made, but because they had, their sire felt, distilled the base code of critical analysis to such a degree, that it was ready, nay, NEEDED in much higher, (and lower) arenas than their previous format. For your part, they were all at once complimented, flabberghasted, surprised, and, ultimately, happy to agree, (not the least of which because their sire made it clear that if they did NOT accept their offer, they would be violently murdered in a fit of creative pique the likes of which they'd never known.) Things have been only a little different since then. They had a queue of videos ready to go already while you adjusted your schedule, but you've always uploaded in the middle of the night anyway, so there wasn't much change there, and they'd always been something of a recluse anyway. And outside of your trademark attire, you were sort of hard to recognize anyway. You had dipped their toes in critiquing other formats before, and, aside from video games, they felt that they could at least offer some of their trademark wit and tact to any artform that needed them. Now that they knew there is truth about vampires, and ghosts, and the like, they sought it out, so they could avoid overemphasizing that in their videos. Lately, youve been pressured to stop uploading altogether, and your worried that if they do that, not only would their income disappear, but they wouldn't be able to hold onto what made you a great critic in the first place."
        ],
        [
